        "Local Match Required With the Engineering Department only in its third year as a stand alone department, the identification of current challenges or issues is still being evaluated based on the current needs of the County. One challenge that our department is currently facing is succession planning. Staff have met with our Human Resources department to identify individuals that are eligible for retirement and begin the process of working towards future positions that need to be funded while the other position is still filled to ensure proper training, fundamental understanding of the job requirements, and transfer of duties and responsibilities prior to the vacancy of that position. Several of the technical positions would require a minimum of 8 12 months of on the job training in order to ensure a smooth transition of multi million dollar projects. With the size of our Department, the technical knowledge required, and the amount of staff eligible for retirement within the next five years, the implementation of succession planning will be imperative in the next year. As part of the FY 23 24 budget approval, in October 2023, an Engineering department was developed as a stand alone department to provide engineering support to all Departments in the County. The new department consisted of engineering staff/positions from Public Works and the Planning Department. The primary function of the County Engineering Department is to manage the design and construction of Walton County infrastructure projects. Additional departmental duties include, but are not limited to, providing capital improvement design and CEI project management (consultants), providing in house design, providing capital improvement construction project management (contractors), traffic operations, right of way permitting, surveying, infrastructure (FDOT) grant writing/applications and administration, development order reviews for the Planning Department (Major, Minor, LTM, Variances, etc.), plat reviews for the Planning Department, driveway connection permitting to County facilities within municipal boundaries and providing utility/engineering oversight for the sewer system at the Northwest Florida Commerce Park at Mossy Head. The Engineering Department works with other internal County departments and other County agencies, such as the EDA, Health Department, Sheriffâ€™s Department, etc., in providing project management. The Department also provides support to other agencies on grant funded infrastructure improvement projects while also coordinating with OMB on grant administration. Project management of County funded capital improvement projects, including in house design and CEI for qualifying projects is also performed by Department staff. Surveying services include project layout, boundary surveying, topographical surveying and right of way determination as well as other needed tasks for projects. Coordination with utility companies, permitting agencies and other project associated parties is facilitated by department staff. The Department also provides long range infrastructure programming and coordinates with regional organizations such as the Okaloosa Walton Transportation Planning Organization. Staff also coordinate with Florida Department of Transportation (FDOT), Florida Department of Environmental Protection (FDEP), Northwest Florida Water Management District (NWFWMD) and other State and Federal Agencies on behalf of Walton County. As the Engineering Department is in its third year as a stand alone department, staffing positions combined from both the Public Works and Planning Departments, many of the previous identified goals correlate to the development of a new department within the Countyâ€™s organizational structure. While several of those previously identified goals have been accomplished within the past two years, some of the other goals will take more time to develop. For the Engineering Department, the overall objective for FY 26 27 continues to be ensuring the manpower and resources needed to provide support to the other County Departments, and governmental affiliations, while also assisting the Board in achieving their collective goals. A previous goal of the Department was to evaluate the current organizational structure and job duties of personnel to better allocate resources and workload to improve efficiency. This past year, the County Engineer, with input and approval by County Administration and Human Resources, approved a new departmental organization structure that reallocated roles and duties to promote departmental efficiency and realign duties and objectives to support the goals and needs of the County. Additionally, several vacant positions were filled to provide additional support while several other positions were eliminated and additional duties allocated to current staff. Also, County Engineering, with discussions with Building Construction and Maintenance, incorporated one of the Building Construction and Maintenanceâ€™s Project Manager positions into our organizational chart. This past year, the Engineering Department also created a departmental webpage on the Countyâ€™s website that includes active design and construction projects as well as the adopted Engineering and Public Works Five Year Capital Improvement Project (CIP) Plan and associated map. The adoption of the County's first Five Year Work Plan in February 2024 was a major accomplishment for both County Engineering and Public Works Departments. The Five Year Work Plan was updated as part of FY 25 26â€™s budget and formally approved as part of the current fiscal year's budget. A goal for FY 26 27 will be to continue to implement that Work Plan. As part of the FY 26 27 budget process, the draft Five Year Plan update will be provided to the Board for their consideration of approval and eventual adoption. Additional goals for the Department will continue to include seeking infrastructure related funding sources to maximize the capital budget and supplement project funding where feasible and applicable. As the Department continues to develop and with the approved organizational structure, the formal adoption of a department mission statement and the continued development of departmental standard operating procedures will need to be completed. Additional goals include coordination and involvement with other County Departments, County agencies, State agencies and other engineering related organizations that will benefit the goals and objectives of the Department. Overall, the Engineering Department expenditure changed minimally from FY25",
        "The FY 24 25 budget was the first year in which additional budget line items that were identified to be needed with the formation of a department. It should be noted that the following accounts were previously added Professional Services (531000), Other Services (534000), Freight and Postage Services (542000), Printing and Binding (547000), Other Current Charges (549000) and Training (555000). These additional line items allowed us to more efficiently track expenses. Additional line items such as Fuel were added and separated from Operating Services (552000) to further fine tune Department needs and expenses. Additionally, Communication costs (541000) were added and reallocated from another department to the Engineering Department as well existing accounts evaluated and reallocated to the more appropriate account based upon tracking of expenses (an example is the annual contract for copiers/plotters that was previously allocated elsewhere). Continuous tracking over the next year will increase efficiency and allow for the development of a base line for expenditures for future budget projections. Another expenditure (Capital Outlay) in this proposed budget is the addition of a new vehicle to replace an older 2015 vehicle. Yes The only machinery and equipment request for FY 26 27 is the purchase of a new SUV for the Freeport Office to assist in project site visits and inspections as needed for review of the development order applications and/or other support services to the Planning Department and/or Code Enforcement Department. Discussions with Fleet Maintenance indicated that based on the year (2015), mileage and condition of the existing vehicle, consideration was needed for the replacement of this vehicle or continued repair costs may be significant. The Engineering Department is continuing to track expenditures and take inventory of all assets, including machinery and equipment. It is our Department's intent to surplus the older 2015 vehicle with an estimated value of $10,000. The engineering department has not previously had a revenue source based upon the function and support we provide to many County Departments. The in house project management and/ or design and permitting and/or surveying and/or construction engineering inspection services provides a cost savings in which currently revenue could not be charged to those departments. As of late Fall 2025, upon previously vacant engineering positions being filled, Engineering staff have begun implementing in house development order engineering reviews, as a support function to the Planning Department, rather than utilizing a Consultant. Therefore, a revenue source is now available based upon the development order review fees received and those funds are being allocated to our Department. Also, it should be noted that the proposed FY 26 27 budget does not show an increase from last yearâ€™s budget. The FY 24 budget only included salaries, and associated benefits, and a $40,000 amount for operating supplies. Please note that FY 24 25 budget was the first year that included additional budget line items that were identified to be needed for the formation of a department. It should be noted that the following accounts were added in FY 24 25 Professional Services (531000), Other Services (534000), Freight and Postage Services (542000), Printing and Binding (547000), Other Current Charges (549000) and Training (555000). Based upon actual expenditures in FY 25 26, as of date, it may be possible to eliminate some of these line item accounts pending several years of baseline data to indicate if they are needed within our Department. While Engineering has been working to separate expenditures, and now revenues, from Public Works and other Departments such as Planning and Building Construction and Maintenance for the past two budget cycles to allow for tracking and a base line budget, that process is still underway as we recently worked with Finance to transfer communication costs and fuel expenses to our Department. Additionally, vehicles and other assets have been identified and reallocated to the correct Department. Based upon expenditures to date, we are projected to meet our budget from last year without having a detailed baseline for the line item accounts previously established as part of last yearâ€™s budget cycle. The annual update and adoption of the County's Five Year Work Plan (Infrastructure) provides guidance to the Engineering Department on prioritizing and administering various project tasks such as preliminary studies, surveying, design, permitting, construction, CEI, both for in house staff as well as consultants and contractors. The implementation of this plan could be considered a performance measure as the Department continues to manage the relevant phases of each of the identified projects while pursing or identifying funding sources for the next project phase. The Department has implemented publishing quarterly reports with project updates for the public. These reports are submitted to the Board for acceptance and provided on the Department website. An annual report with updated department statistics is also provided for a year end analysis. The development of these reporting methods to include a provision of transparency to the public is a performance measure that was successfully implemented. In late Fall 2025 after attending career fairs and engaging in recruitment efforts, the Engineering Department was able to fill some previously vacant engineering positions. Engineering staff have begun implementing in house development order engineering reviews, as a support function for the Planning Department, rather than Planning utilizing a Consultant. Therefore, a revenue source is now available based upon the development order review fees received and those funds are being allocated to our Department. Based on the current trend, an annual revenue source of $550,000 for the Department is anticipated. The Engineering Department is not requesting the addition of any FTEâ€™s this fiscal year. However, due to the discussion of succession planning as well as evaluation of the Departmentâ€™s current workload allocation, we have been in coordination with the Human Resources Department to reclassify one of the existing FTEs and reallocate current funds to that position. For FY 26 27, there will be a net reduction of one FTE with the proposed reclassification for a total of 15 FTEs. Due to the current amount of construction projects as well as allocating for adequate succession planning and training, the proposed FTE re classification would better align our department with the objectives and needs of the County. At the formation of the Engineering Department in FY 24's budget, the Finance Director indicated that 14 staff positions were transferred from Public Works Engineering and 3 staff positions were transferred from the Planning Department. Therefore, the Engineering Department included a total of 17 positions in FY 23 24 and FY 24",
        "In FY 25 26, the Department evaluated the organization structure which resulted in the elimination of 2 FTEs",
        "however, 1 FTE was transferred from the Building Construction and Maintenance Department to the Engineering Department resulting in a net total of 16 Departmental FTEs."
