      "description": "Approved true (USE) Operating Budget Template 850000.0 0 850000.0 During the FY25/26, the Environmental Resource department continued the mission of advancing the County's MS4/NPDES program by mapping the County's stormwater infrastructure. Additionally, staff from the Environmental Resource Department continued to play an active role in the Choctawhatchee Bay Estuary Coalition as the Interim Executive Director, managing and facilitating the Choctawhatchee Bay Estuary Program. Staff assisted with regional watershed efforts within the states of Florida and Alabama. Staff also worked with on legislative efforts to work towards National Estuary Program designation for the Choctawhatchee Bay Estuary Program. During the FY25/26, the Environmental Resource Department provided grant and funding request assistance and grant management for many projects that included ecosystem restoration, planning assistance for resiliency, Department of Health Coastal Branch Expansion, State and Federal Legislative funding including transportation needs, agriculture centers, historical sites, etc. Staff also successfully organized 2025 Coastal Dune Lake Week, celebrating one of our Countyâ€™s unique ecosystems and providing education to both our citizens and tourists. Challenges Walton County is growing and so are the needs within the County, however the County is also facing potential financial challenges with the threat of loss of property taxes and therefore every Department is looking for ways to trim their budgets and become more effective and efficient. Issues The Walton County Environmental Resource team is a small, but mighty team. In effort to become more effective and efficient the department is requesting additional equipment for both the water resources and NPDES efforts. Environmental Resources is responsible for ensuring compliance of navigational signage, derelict vessel removal coordination, and artificial reef deployments. These efforts require staff to be on the water surveying the waterways of Walton County on a more frequent basis. Adding a vessel to the Environmental Resources fleet will ensure regular compliance in the waterways of Walton County. The proposed vessel is not to exceed $175,000.00. Environmental Resources is responsible for mapping and inspecting all County owned stormwater infrastructure. There are over 1,048 miles of County maintained roads that need to be mapped and inspected. To more efficiently inspect this infrastructure, the Environmental Resource Department is in need of an ATV and associated trailer for hauling. Opportunities The Walton County Environmental Resource Department will continue to solicit and coordinate appropriate grants and other funding opportunities for improving water quality, environmental and ecotourism opportunities in Walton County to help leverage County funds and achieve County initiatives. Walton County Environmental Resource Department is responsible for providing environmental support functions to County government, citizens, as well as federal, state and local government agencies on environmental issues regarding the protection of natural resources in Walton County. In FY26/27, the Environmental Resource Department will continue to help support environmental efforts throughout Walton County including advancements of artificial reefs, involvement in with the Choctawhatchee Bay Estuary Coalition, education and outreach efforts for the coastal dune lakes, management of the Habitat Conservation Plan, County wide resiliency efforts, management of invasive species within the County right of ways and County owned properties, management of the MS4/NPDES Stormwater Management Program, support with regulation of wildlife lighting, regulation of small quantity generators, coordination of derelict vessel removal, maintenance of No Wake Zones, ecotourism planning and input, recreational improvements to our natural resources, environmental assessments for County related projects and land purchases, wetland line reviews petroleum tank compliance, well compliance, permitting and mitigation, involvement and coordination of the endangered species within Walton County, RESTORE/NRDA, involvement in Walton Beautiful, and help solicit grant opportunities associated with water quality, environmental restoration, ecotourism, and resiliency efforts. The Environmental Resources Department is a small, but mighty team. The team provides support to almost every department in the County through compliance support, permitting support, natural resource protection, education and outreach, and grant writing for Walton County. We provide support and coordination for many federal, state, and local agencies as well as both the public and visitors of Walton County, Florida. Two major changes to the Environmental Resources Department Annual budget for FY26/27 includes additional equipment and contracting the SQG program. In effort to more efficiency operate, Environmental Resource Department is proposing the purchase of three larger equipment purchases including a vessel, ATV and associated trailer. This equipment will allow staff to advance both the waterways and NPDES programs for Walton County. The State of Florida delegates regulation of small quantity generator facilities to local governments. This program requires routine inspections of these facilities and compliance action as necessary. The Environmental Resource Department has been trying for the past few years to get staff trained in the program, however, it has been determined that the program may need a dedicated staff member to ensure that proper compliance is achieved. In lue, of hiring a new FTE to implement the SQG program in Walton County, management is recommending contracting with the Emerald Coast Regional Planning Council to include in their existing program. Currently, the Emerald Coast Regional Planning Council (ECRPC) currently supports all the counties in the western panhandle of Florida, except Walton County. The contract with ECRPC will be approximately $25,000 per year to provide the required regulation and compliance support. The Environmental Resource team will continue to provide education and outreach to the public on small quantity generators. Yes Environmental Resources is proposing the purchase of three large equipment items including a vessel with associated trailer, (1) ATV, and trailer for the ATV. These equipment purchases will help make the department more effective and efficient with both waterway programs and the NPDES program. Performance Measures MS4/NPDES â€¢ Education and Outreach â€¢ Mailouts â€¢ Rain barrel Workshop â€¢ Mapping County Stormwater Infrastructure â€¢ Annual Report Coastal Dune Lakes â€¢ Plan, organize, and facilitate Coastal Dune Lake Advisory Board Meetings 4 â€¢ Plan, organize, and facilitate Coastal Dune Lake Week annually in the Fall. Walton County Resiliency Efforts â€¢ Adaptation Plan process to begin in 2026 (Estimated Completion 2028). Walton County Artificial Reef Deployment Increased public outreach on environmental related topics. No new revenue changes are anticipated outside of potential grant awards that will be project specific. Currently, the Environmental Resource Department is comprised of (1) Environmental Manager, (1) Environmental Planner (VACANT to be retitled and filled FY 25/26), and (2) Environmental Scientist I. No additional staff changes are being requested in this upcoming fiscal year.",
